        "text": "Monoco&#x27;s weapon add additional effects to masks or makes them easier to control. Personally, I find Joyaro is the best weapon for him as it starts him at Almighty. Monoco&#x27;s Gradient attacks are not affected by the Wheel or and don&#x27;t typically move it, however his Mighty Strike is excellent as it automatically moves it to Almighty. Break point is handy in a pinch as it fills the Break bar and breaks an enemy instantly............but for 3 Gradient charges its a huge waste if you have better options in the party. Monoco has a lot of options and a lot roles he can play at once, support, offensive, defensive, healer, it really comes down to which skills you set up. This is why it is easy to get new skills as he is a near essential party member in Act 2 (especially if you spend some time backtracking to collect skills). That said, once you start exploring the world in Act 3 Monoco even with all his skills learnt quickly becomes less useful compared to more specialized party members, he deal\n\nMonoco is named after the developer team's dog and is the party's Blue Mage. For people not familiar with the term it's essentially a character who specializes in learning and using skills used by enemies. Monoco is very much this kind of character as he doesn't have a standard skill tree and has more skills than any other character. Unlike everyone else who gets skill points when they level up to learn new skills, Monoco gains new skills each time he defeats a new enemy type. This only applies when he is in the party though. Monoco has a grand total of 46 skills he can learn from enemies (not counting his Gradient skills which he learns from Bond events like everyone else). I am 90% sure that most people reading this came looking for a list of locations where they can quickly go and find all the enemies on the skill list, so let me save you some time and sanity, rather than running around all over the map trying to find old enemies though you are welcome to.\n\nYou can find all the enemies which give Monoco skills in the Endless Tower in Act 3 with the exception Gross Tete who is found outside Coastal Cave one time OR as a normal enemy in the Flying Manor. For those not willing to wait I will just let you know that simply by proceeding and advancing with the story after gaining Monoco you will have a chance to encoutner more than 75% of the enemies you need to beat for the skills as many reappear in The Monolith including boss types. This isn't something to stress over. With that out of the way, lets talk about Monoco's Beastial Wheel. All of Monoco's skills come with 2 additional aspects, they have a move value and a Mask. You can consider the masks the same Maelle's stances, they have no effect themselves but skills used on a coinciding mask are upgraded with greater damage or effects. In addition when any skill is used the move value will move the wheel the number of spaces listed.\n\nMonoco's weapon add additional effects to masks or makes them easier to control. Personally, I find Joyaro is the best weapon for him as it starts him at Almighty. Monoco's Gradient attacks are not affected by the Wheel or and don't typically move it, however his Mighty Strike is excellent as it automatically moves it to Almighty. Break point is handy in a pinch as it fills the Break bar and breaks an enemy instantly............but for 3 Gradient charges its a huge waste if you have better options in the party. Monoco has a lot of options and a lot roles he can play at once, support, offensive, defensive, healer, it really comes down to which skills you set up. This is why it is easy to get new skills as he is a near essential party member in Act 2 (especially if you spend some time backtracking to collect skills). That said, once you start exploring the world in Act 3 Monoco even with all his skills learnt quickly becomes less useful compared to more specialized party members, he deal",
